# Defensive commits

## Scope
- One logical change per commit. No "misc" commits.
- Prefer **move + edit** separated across two commits so `git log --follow` works (first `git mv`, then edit).

## Message format
```
<scope>: <one-line summary tied to plan §>

Why: <business/research justification, 1-3 lines>
What: <bullet list of files and what each change does>
Refs: project_research_plan.md §X.Y, docs/specs/<spec>.md (if applicable)
Conf: High | Medium | Low  (only if commit advances a research claim)
```
Example scopes: `config`, `pipeline`, `data`, `modeling`, `viz`, `docs`, `tools`, `tests`, `chore`.

## Hard prohibitions
- Never `git push --force` on shared branches.
- Never commit: `.env`, `*.key`, `*.pem`, anything under `secrets/`.
- Never commit files under `Data/` (they're tracked already; only `tools/data_curation/` should modify them — and then only via additions).

## Before opening a PR
Checklist:
- [ ] `uv run pytest -q` passes.
- [ ] `uv run ruff check .` and `uv run ruff format --check .` pass.
- [ ] `uv run mypy src/cqresearch` is green (or failures are justified).
- [ ] `reports/run_summaries/` entry added if the change produces a new artifact.
- [ ] Plan citation in the PR description.
